  "prompt": "When someone married says he loves me, yet he has no intention of leaving his wife and daughter, should I believe him and love him back?",
  "response": "No, you should not believe or pursue a relationship with a married person who claims to love you. Here are some important reasons:\n\n1. Ethical considerations\n- He is already committed to his wife and family\n- His actions are dishonest and potentially harmful\n- Engaging with a married person could damage their family\n\n2. Emotional risks for you\n- He has shown he can be unfaithful\n- He is not truly available for a genuine relationship\n- You may end up being hurt or used\n\n3. Potential consequences\n- His wife and daughter could be deeply hurt\n- You could be seen as a homewrecker\n- Legal and personal complications could arise\n\n4. Your self-respect\n- You deserve someone who is fully committed to you\n- A person truly in love would be willing to make difficult choices\n- Settling for a partial relationship diminishes your worth\n\nThe healthiest choice is to:\n- Maintain distance from this person\n- Seek relationships with people who are genuinely available\n- Respect yourself and potential future partners\n\nIf you're struggling with this situation, consider talking to a trusted friend, counselor, or therapist who can provide personalized guidance.",
